	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				My main character is a 47th level High Elf Cleric on Bertoxxulous. Regarding above posts, I agree with the idea that there are combat and support clerics. I consider my character to be both. I wear platemail armor with high AC which also gives mana and/or wisdom. Examples are the Charred Guardian Shield, Runed-Mithril Armor and, although I have yet to attain any due to recent Fear Plane beef ups, Etheral Mist Platemail.<BR>
<BR>
As a cleric beyond level 40, I have no regrets about my race/class choices. I stare at a meditation screen, but you learn to figure out what is going on by listening carefulling to what your group is saying, watching the health bars and of course standing up to heal I get a chance to look around. Life at lower levels is much different. Your melee skills aren't very good after the first few levels and your attack spells don't really do much until level 14. <BR>
<BR>
The fact that you can wear platemail isn't important until bronze armor becomes available to you, and unless you are a twink (eek!) that won't be until late teens early 20ies. 14 is actually not the god send level many think it is. Healing is actually too powerful to really use often at that level. It only becomes praticle at level 19 or so, which is when Druids and Shamans get it anyway. Level 19 IS the god send that many make it out to be. As are 24 and 29. The Courage, Center, Daring (lvl 19)line of spells are extremely powerful. At higher levels, many more people ask me for Resolution (the final spell in that line) much more than they ask a Druid for SoW or other common buffs. <BR>
<BR>
One thing many people mistake about Clerics is that we can easily solo at any level. At level 47 I can do 585 damage to undead mobs, and 511 to everything else. I also have 275 damage wide range area of effect and 90 damage stun. With these spells, and root, I can easily solo Sand Giants, Hill Giants, Guards, Spectres, and many other high level mobs. The XP for me is actually better soloing than it is in a group.<BR>
<BR>
OK, so with the general abilities covered (I won't overlap, lots is already covered in posts before this and I have already done lots of overlapping) I feel I should give general play tips.<BR>
<BR>
The first thing: the whole idea that Clerics should be doing everything for free is totally wrong. Believe me, I still need all the platinum I can get at level 47. I'm still buying high level plate and spells. Charge a small price for those heals (assuming your not grouped, obviously don't charge group members for your services, LOL) cures and buffs. You will always need the money. Being Cleric-like is one thing, getting the armor and spells you need for the next level however is far more important. There is nothing worse than not having the money to buy all your next rank spells. If you can twink 50 thousand plat, you should be ok ...<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Symbol&quot; spells. These spells cost money. 13pp a cast at my level. If your group expects you to pay for them yourself, you need to find a new group. Clerics get hit the hardests for cash as it is, and no other class (short of firing arrows) is expected to spend anything more than mana in a group situation. If party members want Symbol, and they provide the gems for you, then it's not a problem. If it's a friend or guildmember, once and a while, not a problem. Spending 200pp a day buffing your party, problem. (Then people ask you why you still have bronze at level 30, believe me you want to take their heads off)<BR>
<BR>
At level 47, I don't charge for buffs and heals anymore. I give them out freely whenever I walk around in a city or dungeon or wherever. The amount I could charge just isn't very much money anymore. I make lots of new friends when I make a level 9 character have 800 hp and 70 resistance to all areas. This is the great part about being a cleric. A level 47 wizard could be much more boring in that they can't buff anyone and all they do is burn, burn, burn. <BR>
<BR>
At my level, although I usually don't say it because it gets everyone else mad (hehe) I know when I have been the key factor in a big battle. It's usually ever other fight I get this feeling. 'Beind every great group, there is a great cleric.' This is another perk of being a cleric, you are almost always the most important group member and if you can live with no one else but you knowing that you are that key group member, the rewards are great. <BR>
<BR>
On my server, I am the fourth highest cleric. The three above me are all level 50 (argh!). I find that there are a surplus of level 30-40 clerics, but I know also that the drop out rate for my class is high at that level range. This results in a lack of 40-50 clerics. I usually walk into a dungeon because someone has called me from many zones away in need of a cleric for their group. This is another great thing about being a cleric, especially at my level: you always get those teleports you need. Wizards die lots (no really, they do!) and they need resusitate and resurrect a lot. They are always willing to provide you with a group and a teleport when they want their XP back! I can't remember the last time I had to take the boat.<BR>
<BR>
Another cleric perk: divine aura line of spells. This has been mentioned lots above, so I won't get into detail. THIS LEVEL 1 SPELL IS THE BEST SPELL A CLERIC GETS. I chain cast this spell (as if that were possible, I wish). The regeneration time on it is about 5 or 10 minutes. When available, I always cast if I have mobs on me. It is the best anti-taunt I know of. I will have three versions of this spell at level 49, and I keep them all memorized. I always leave one for emergency. The higher level versions regenerate HP and can be cast on group members as well...<BR>
<BR>
I think I've rambled enough. I hope I have provided some information, more geared towards clerics at higher levels, that has not already been provided above.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
